I’ve never cared too much to know my loc count. Mostly because I know that everyone’s hair is different and I don’t want anyone to think if they have the same number of locs as someone else that their locs will look the same. The courseness and thickness of your hair plays a big role. And also how you care for your locs.

I have a loc count video on my YouTube channel from many years ago - before I combined many of my locs and before I shaved the back. 

For this video, I counted from the root. I have many locs that I’ve combined that still have 2 or 3 locs at the ends. I counted those as one. Some of those ends I’ve trimmed off over the years. 

But for good reference, my current number is 97 - give or take (it is a frustrating experience to recount lol). 

What is your loc count? 

Feel free to remix this Reel and post your number :)

Whew! I finally washed and retwisted 🙌🏾 Then I decided that I’d love some curls or crinkles. So I braided it up for a 2-in-1 style. I think it took me 2-3 hours to retwist and braid. I’ll rock these braids for some days or maybe a week then unravel them for a crinkly style.
How many years in are you in your loc journey? 13 or 14 years here.

10 Reasons Why I ✂️ My Long Locs:

1. For sanitary reasons. Two reasons here. First (and foremost!), bending over to use a public stall and having your locs sweep the floor or worse - your locs taking a dip in the toilet makes me gag. I literally cut those off; I can’t live with them anymore. Secondly, reaching over to blow out a candle and your locs take a dip in the hot wax is a no-no when you are “team no wax”. I end up just cutting those pieces off because it’s so hard to remove. 

2. Neck Pain. Maybe it’s because I spend many hours every day on the sewing machine, so I may keep my head at an awkward angle. That combined with heavy locs puts a lot of strain on my neck and requires frequent massages.

3. Back Pain. Especially while washing - so so heavy. Wash day started to get very tiring. I typically wash in the shower and the weight was making the experience very cumbersome. 

4. Dry Time. In the beginning of my journey I would wash early in the day then airdry. But once my locs got long I needed a better solution. I can’t use an overhead dryer with artificial heat due to having sebborheic dermatitis. Couldn’t walk around with long wet heavy locs, especially in the winter. The @myrevair dryer has helped drastically with cutting my dry time down. I can now completely dry my locs in less than an hour. 

5. Ponytail. My ponytails would lead to a stiff neck. It was just too much pressure hanging in one direction. 

6. Bun Life. I love having a big top bun. But after an hour it gives me a headache. 

7. Sleep situation. I wear my loccrush bonnet when I sleep. I was at the XXL size and at that length (past my tailbone), my bonnet was full. In order for my neck to be comfortable while I slept, I would use my bonnet as my pillow and remove my actual pillows. Now after my trim, I can fit an XL or maybe even a Large bonnet - I’ll have to make myself some new ones and see. 

8. Style Flow. Length and weight weighs down styles like crinkles and curls. I like fullness when it comes to curly styles. They will also last longer now. 

Continued in comment section..
My first plan was to go bra-strap-length. But I decided on waist-length to test the waters first.

Who said locs weren’t versatile? Wrong. My hair had never gotten this long before locs. I was able to cut inches off and still have long hair. I love being able to switch it up. And can you tell I am absolutely loving my new cut ?

I’ve been following my medicated regime (shampoo, oil, and ointment) prescribed by my dermatologist and it really helps with managing sebborheic dermatitis. I’m not really to unravel just yet.

Ok I had to get myself together real quick but didn’t have the time nor energy. So I made a batch of flaxseed gel and retwisted a few rows in the front back into a ponytail. This style saves me hours!

What works for me is to wash my locs as often as I NEED to. If your hair and scalp need cleansing, that’s your cue.  1-2 weeks is my limit. Your don’t have to retwist every time. I pay more attention to my scalp than my hair when it comes to washing. I have gone months and months without retwisting. Sometimes I just retwist the front (as in my previous reel), which saves me hours on time. 

I use a medicated shampoo prescribed by my dermatologist to wash.

I get my best braidout results when I start on freshly washed hair. I retwist my roots in sections of three locs at a time. Then I braid those locs tightly and secure the end with a rubberband. 

The next step is key.. 

You must allow your hair to dry COMPLETELY before unraveling the braids otherwise you’ve wasted your time. 

I typically wear the braids for up to a week before unraveling, giving me two solid styles.

I keep it really simple. I cleanse and exfoliate morning and night. And stay moisturized with shea butter and protected with sunscreen. I drink plenty of water and maintain a healthy diet - this is important!

In case you missed it, I posted a YouTube video a few days ago. I’m getting comfortable in front of the video camera again. I think it’s about time I film my skin care video. What do you think?
A quick brow clean up to save the day. I don’t wear makeup so keeping the brows fresh is how I glam.

Absolutely! 

My locs didn’t start to flourish until I took the health of my hair into my own hands. Nobody will learn how to care for your hair better than you can. Don’t be intimidated by retwisting - once you get your technique down, it’s easy.

1. Don’t overboil. If you boil too hard and too long, it will be too thick to strain. 

2. After boiling, let it sit at room temperature for a few hours until you are ready to use it. It will continue to thicken — this is my favorite consistency! When you use it straight from the stove or the fridge, it will be more thin. 

3. Refrigerate what you are not using right away. Use within a week.
How to make Flaxseed Gel from loccrush.com

I normally make my gel and sit it on the counter until I’m ready to use it a few hours later. It thickens as it cools. If you want even more thickness, leave it out overnight and it’ll turn into this 😍. I wouldn’t leave it out for a longer time frame because it is completely fresh, no preservatives, and would need refrigeration. My flaxseed gel kit is available on my website: loccrush.com. Short answer - when I feel up to it. My roots are thick-thick, y’all. And I’m not always up for the task of retwisting. In the first couple years into my loc journey, I washed and retwisted every 2 weeks. I was over-committed lol. That was unnecessary. 

Truth is there is no one right answer. Wash your hair as often as your scalp needs cleansing and retwist to your liking. Listen to the needs of your hair and respond.

I currently wash every 1-2 weeks and I don’t retwist every time. I may just do two or three rows in the front for a neat look (yes, the back is an Afro at the roots 🤣).
I may retwist my whole head every few months or so - really whenever there is a special occasion in which I want that fresh look.

I feel like the less I do the more it grows.

Have you ever crocheted your locs?

Because I often wash but don’t always retwist, I get a lot of hairs that grow outside the loc - frizzies. 

Listen, I am no professional so this is not a tutorial. Just a watch-along while I figure it out and do what I do 💛 If you know a loc crochet professional, tag them below. 

The crochet tool I used is linked in my profile in my Amazon faves. 

The method I used is to retwist the loose hair around the loc a few inches at a time, starting at the root. Then crochet a few angles around each section as I move down the loc. I didn’t use any product. 

I am very satisfied with the results. This was just one run thru and I see a lot less frizzies.

I had every plan to wake up early, wash my hair, dry it, and retwist it. That didn’t happen. So a quick retwist for the win.

Chunky twists are an easy one for me. Doesn’t take a lot of time on top of the retwist. I washed them retwisted with flaxseed gel. 

I’ll unravel in a few days; won’t be much curl to it because I twisted loosely. But I did retwist the roots so it’ll be a fresh straight style.

I like to 1. Start with a fresh wash and retwist each section as I go. 

2. Separate that section into two. 

3. Twist each section in the opposite direction of your chunky twist direction. 

4. Secure the ends with a rubberband so they won’t unravel.
How long do you keep your twists in for? My scalp is ready to be free after a few days.

My biggest take away from having locs - no one is going to care for my hair like I can. Instead of making an appointment, I opted to do my research and care for my hair myself. I learned what’s best for my hair and scalp.

10 Reasons Why I ✂️ My Long Locs:

1. For sanitary reasons. Two reasons here. First (and foremost!), bending over to use a public stall and having your locs sweep the floor or worse - your locs taking a dip in the toilet makes me gag. I literally cut those off; I can’t live with them anymore. Secondly, reaching over to blow out a candle and your locs take a dip in the hot wax is a no-no when you are “team no wax”. I end up just cutting those pieces off because it’s so hard to remove. 

2. Neck Pain. Maybe it’s because I spend many hours every day on the sewing machine, so I may keep my head at an awkward angle. That combined with heavy locs puts a lot of strain on my neck and requires frequent massages.

3. Back Pain. Especially while washing - so so heavy. Wash day started to get very tiring. I typically wash in the shower and the weight was making the experience very cumbersome. 

4. Dry Time. In the beginning of my journey I would wash early in the day then airdry. But once my locs got long I needed a better solution. I can’t use an overhead dryer with artificial heat due to having sebborheic dermatitis. Couldn’t walk around with long wet heavy locs, especially in the winter. The @myrevair dryer has helped drastically with cutting my dry time down. I can now completely dry my locs in less than an hour. (I have a link to the dryer in my IG profile). 

5. Ponytail. My ponytails would lead to a stiff neck. It was just too much pressure hanging in one direction. 

6. Bun Life. I love having a big top bun. But after an hour it gives me a headache. 

7. Sleep situation. I wear my loccrush bonnet when I sleep. I was at the XXL size and at that length (past my tailbone), my bonnet was full. In order for my neck to be comfortable while I slept, I would use my bonnet as my pillow and remove my actual pillows. Now after my trim, I can fit an XL or maybe even a Large bonnet - I’ll have to make myself some new ones and see. 

8. Style Flow. Length and weight weighs down styles like crinkles and curls. I like fullness when it comes to curly styles. They will also last longer now.
